summary:
Wim van den Bos is a Dutch national and lived in Eastern and Southern Africa for over 15 years. He has vast experience in developmental and private sector development consultancy in various African countries. Recently he returned to the Netherlands. Currently he works as business developer on mostly horti-related consultancy assignments and investment projects in Africa and India.

In Africa he has been involved in various policy advisory studies on public investments in specific horticultural value chains and sustainable land management. Such assignments were conducted for governments and international organisations (e.g. World Bank, NORAD, UNDP) He conducted a number of commercial feasibility studies on prospected horticulture projects and investments in Africa. He further was instrumental in developing value chains for a number of high value crops aiming at inclusion of smallholder farmers. 

Prior to his move to Africa, he was working as a business consultant for an audit and consultancy firm in the Netherlands, advising companies in the agribusiness on investment decisions and fiscal issues. 

Wim holds an MSc in Agricultural Economics and from Wageningen University, The Netherlands, and a post-graduate diploma Public Financial Management from London School of Economics. He is fluent in English. He has field experience in Netherlands, Southern Africa (Malawi, Mozambique, Zambia, Zimbabwe and South Africa), East Africa (Ethiopia, Kenya, Tanzania, Uganda, Rwanda and South Sudan), West Africa (Nigeria, Ghana, Sierra Leone, Ivory Coast) and India.  

Specialties: 
Public-Private Partnership Development, Programme Management, Investment & Feasibility Studies, Horticulture Training & Curriculum Development, Investment Subsidies & Financing;

Value Chain Development, Agricultural Marketing, Contract Farming; 

Microfinance, Microinsurance: Weather Index Insurance;

Social Venturing, Inclusive Investments;
